fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Thinking this way brings at least two benefits: one practical and one conceptual. Practically, I find it makes it easier to calculate the value a compound sentence should take on a valuation. Think again about a valuation w such that w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, and w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, and w(r) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, and suppose you want to know what w(p \land \neg (q \lor r)) is. (This is one of the examples we just looked at.) Now we can proceed as follows: since we know w(p), w(q), and w(r), we can dig into our compound sentence and replace those atomic sentences by the truth values they take on the valuation w. This gives us \mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg (\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} \lor \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}). And now we can proceed step-by-step just as before:
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg (\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} \lor \mathsf {\mathbf {T}})
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \neg \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}
\mathsf {\mathbf {T}} \land \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}
\mathsf {\mathbf {F}} This is just another way to arrive at the same answer, and we're doing the same things along the way. The difference is that going this way gives you a useful notation for writing down intermediate results. That can get really important; the more you try to hold in your head at once, the more likely you are to make a slip-up. By having a simple notation for intermediate results, you can make it much easier to make it through an entire calculation correctly.

